04773nam a22005655i 9780822395904DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223959047 a10.1515/97808223959042doi  a(DE-B1597)552747  a(OCoLC)824824472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aML3503.G4bS55 2013eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a781.63096672231 aShipley, Jesse Weaver, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiving the Hiplife :bCelebrity and Entrepreneurship in Ghanaian Popular Music /cJesse Weaver Shipley. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b54 illustrations, including 9 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction. Aesthetics and Aspiration -- t1. Soul to Soul: Value Transformations and Disjunctures of Diaspora in Urban Ghana -- t2. Hip- Hop Comes to Ghana: State Privatization and an Aesthetic of Control -- t3. Rebirth of Hip: Afro- Cosmopolitanism and Masculinity in Accra's New Speech Community -- t4. The Executioner's Words: Genre, Respect, and Linguistic Value -- t5. Scent of Bodies: Parody as Circulation -- t6. Gendering Value for a Female Hiplife Star: Moral Violence as PerformanceTechnology -- t7. No. 1 Mango Street: Celebrity Labor and Digital Production as Musical Value -- t8. Ghana@50 in the Bronx: Sonic Nationalism and New Diasporic Disjunctures -- tConclusion. Rockstone's Office: Entrepreneurship and the Debt of Celebrity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHiplife is a popular music genre in Ghana that mixes hip-hop beatmaking and rap with highlife music, proverbial speech, and Akan storytelling. In the 1990s, young Ghanaian musicians were drawn to hip-hop's dual ethos of black masculine empowerment and capitalist success. They made their underground sound mainstream by infusing carefree bravado with traditional respectful oratory and familiar Ghanaian rhythms. Living the Hiplife is an ethnographic account of hiplife in Ghana and its diaspora, based on extensive research among artists and audiences in Accra, Ghana's capital city; New York; and London. Jesse Weaver Shipley examines the production, consumption, and circulation of hiplife music, culture, and fashion in relation to broader cultural and political shifts in neoliberalizing Ghana.Shipley shows how young hiplife musicians produce and transform different kinds of value-aesthetic, moral, linguistic, economic-using music to gain social status and wealth, and to become respectable public figures. In this entrepreneurial age, youth use celebrity as a form of currency, aligning music-making with self-making and aesthetic pleasure with business success. Registering both the globalization of electronic, digital media and the changing nature of African diasporic relations to Africa, hiplife links collective Pan-Africanist visions with individualist aspiration, highlighting the potential and limits of social mobility for African youth.The author has also directed a film entitled Living the Hiplife and with two DJs produced mixtapes that feature the music in the book available for free download.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHip-hopzGhana. 0aPopular musiczGhanaxHistory and criticism. 0aRap (Music)zGhanaxHistory and criticism. 0aRap musicianszGhana. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395904zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780